japan 's economic growth likely to slow down next year
japan 's economy is likely to slow down and enter 2005 , as the yen 's appreciation and widening gap between the rich and the poor may undermine the harmonious atmosphere enjoyed in the first half of this year .
analysts point their hopes of supporting japan 's economic growth to china , despite rising political tensions between japan and china , after 10 years of stagnation with high profits and strong consumer spending .
evidence is gradually showing that the japanese economy is likely to decline in early 2005 , particularly if industrial production continues to decline , while manufacturers adjust inventories to avoid overstocking up inventories .
according to the latest method of statistics , japan 's economy in the april - june quarter actually shrank slightly , with only 0.1 percent growth in the july - september quarter , which just escaped the technical slump .
economists are still divided about the strength of the japanese economy .
research staff of the france 's chillida bank estimated that japan 's economic growth could reach 2.3% in real terms in the fiscal year ending march next year and the next fiscal year .
they called the " recovery year 2005 " for reasons : the us economy has returned to the track of recovery steadily and japanese consumer spending has made up for the slowdown in exports .
another pessimistic view is that economists from the pfj predict a growth rate of only 1.8 percent for this fiscal year and a lower growth rate of 0.6 percent for the next fiscal year .
they pointed out the " potential risks " , which means that profits made by manufacturers did not lead to personal gains .
french fm : peace in middle east going to test france - us relations
after meeting with us secretary of state colin powell today , french foreign minister barnier said : the resumption of the middle east peace talks will " test " their transatlantic relations .
after palestinian leader arafat died , france called for holding an international seminar to promote the israeli - palestinian peace process , but no agreement was reached at the end of the meeting between barnier and powell .
barnier flew from paris to washington , where he held lightning talks with powell and his successor , national security adviser condoleezza rice , before heading for brussels to attend a eu summit .
both paris and washington agreed to mend their tight relations after the united states occupied iraq last year , but their differences in resolving the middle east deadlock remain clear .
" we want to improve the future relations between france and the united states , as well as between europe and america , " barnier said after a brief meeting between the us state department and powell .
he said : " i think the test of the core relationship lies in our ability to promote the peace process in palestine and israel . "
barnier earlier this week called for an international seminar on the middle east to be held at an early date in order to take advantage of what he called the " window of opportunity " that emerged after arafat died last month .
however , powell was still unwilling to make a commitment .
he said that the two discussed britain 's plan to hold a meeting attended by palestinians , but did not mention whether to hold a wider range of international meetings .
us officials have indicated that their primary task is to promote peace in israel and palestine and ensure the smooth progress of the palestinian elections next month .
the election will produce a leader who can control muslim militants and restore israeli - palestinian talks .
new japanese , rok talks to be held in january
japan and the republic of korea ( rok ) will start negotiations on a free trade agreement in january next year , japanese foreign minister nobutaka nobutaka nobutaka kawashima said tuesday .
speaking in talks with south korean foreign and trade minister ban ki - moon in kagoshima prefecture in southern japan , nobusuo nobutaka kawashima said both tokyo and seoul hoped to sign a free trade agreement by the end of 2005 and to resume negotiations as soon as possible .
japanese prime minister junichiro koizumi and south korean president roh moo - hyun held a summit on the 17 th , during which roh moo - hyun urged tokyo authorities to be careful on the issue of imposing economic sanctions against north korea .
north korea kidnapped several japanese nationals during the cold war , and prime minister koizumi is facing tremendous pressure from people demanding punishment against north korea .
after japanese researchers concluded last week that the remains provided by pyongyang to prove that the two hostages had died were not the remains of the parties concerned , they were very angry about the kidnapping of the family members of the victims .
apart from the kidnapping issue , koizumi and roh moo - hyun agreed that the six - party talks aimed at preventing north korea from developing nuclear weapons should resume as soon as possible .
no concrete results have been achieved in the previous three rounds of six - party talks since north korea secretly developed its nuclear weapons program triggered confrontation in october 2002 .
north korea later boycotted the fourth round of six - party talks originally scheduled for september this year .
the six - party talks are south korea , north korea , the united states , china , japan and russia .
thai prime minister expected to win february election
thailand 's prime minister , when thaksin was about to enter 2005 , was confident that he could win his second four - year term but his reputation had been damaged as he failed to stop the bloody insurgency .
thailand 's national elections are scheduled for february 6 , 2006 , with thaksin and his political opponents preparing for the election , most analysts expect a victory despite the outbreak of serious violence and bird flu in the south .
twelve people have died of bird flu in thailand this year and bird flu has swept across most of asia . however , in thailand , it is particularly serious . the thai government admitted that it has " made mistakes " in handling the epidemic .
but the health problem is unlikely to allow thaksin to be reelected , and on the contrary , many are asking what extent he would win and what significance would he have to the muslim rebellion in southern provinces ?
" the phenomenon here is that he enjoys popular support no matter how you look at dassin , " senate foreign relations committee chairman clesak told afp .
he said , " however , the situation will start to collapse next year . if you look at the accumulation of wealth ( his family and people around him ) and the unfair and violent situation in society . "
it is precisely due to social injustice and violence that turmoil erupted in the most heavily muslim region in thailand , and sporadic insurgency started in the first month of the month .
since january this year , muslim militants have targeted buddhist believers , government officials and security forces . they have also carried out bomb attacks and decoupled . so far , more than 560 people have been killed and 100 others are missing .
