russian space agency denies rocket fuel causing child illness
russia 's space agency denied the report that children in its vicinity suffered from serious illness due to the highly toxic rocket fuel emitted during the launch of the spacecraft at kazakhstan 's bekonsha space base , a weekly scientific journal reported .
the standard of people suffering from internal secretions and blood diseases in the polluted areas is twice that of the general areas , the nature science journal quoted a research report today .
the research was carried out by a group of russian scientists led by pop pathologist rudolf koglov .
russian space agency responded , " space related activities have no direct impact on residents ' health . "
the research , quoted by the nature science journal , mainly focuses on children in the altai republic .
the republic of altay is located in the mountainous region on the edge of siberia .
the altay was selected as the target of research because of unburned fuel , especially ammonia .
in some cases , the russian space launch mission uses ucb as fuel for the previous several stages .
between 1998 and 2000 , the health records of about 1,000 children in the two polluting areas will be compared with the health records of 3,300 children in nearby uncontaminated areas .
the number of children in the most polluted areas is nearly twice the number of unpolluted groups and the duration of treatment is twice the same , the nature science journal reported .
