( international ) united nations warns of more drug addicts worldwide in 2005
xinhua news agency , vienna , december 17 ( reporter song guocheng ) un drug control and crime prevention executive director staca warned in a press release on the 17 th that due to the increase in the production of heroin in afghanistan , it is estimated that the black price of heroin in the world will stabilize and its purity will increase in 2005 , leading to the death of more drug addicts .
costa has issued a warning to health and anti - drug authorities in europe and surrounding countries , urging them to be concerned about the latest trends in drug cultivation and international drug crimes in afghanistan and to take appropriate preventive measures .
according to statistics provided by the un office for drug control and crime prevention in vienna , when opium crop cultivation was banned in afghanistan in 2001 , the country 's heroin output dropped by 94 percent , and the purity rate of heroin in the black market in europe dropped by 50 percent in the second year .
from 2000 to 2002 , the number of drug addicts in europe has decreased by 20 percent .
he said that compared with 2003 , afghanistan 's opium growing area has increased by 64 percent this year , with the output of heroin reaching more than 500 tons , which is higher than the transaction volume of heroin on the black market in the world a year . this trend means that the number of drug users and drug death have increased accordingly .
costa rica holds that the source of narcotics in afghanistan has constituted a " clear and practical threat " to global efforts against drugs . the increase in the supply of heroin on the black market means a " death " judgment for drug addicts .
according to estimates , the number of deaths due to excessive use of drugs in the world is about 100,000 a year .
